\section{Vital32: Complete Build Guide}

Vital32 is the primary biosensing node of LifeSphere. It is built on the ESP32 WROOM-32 microcontroller and communicates with Firebase via Wi-Fi. This section provides complete wiring specifications, firmware architecture, and sensor calibration procedures sufficient to build and deploy a functional Vital32 unit from scratch.

\subsection{Complete Component List}

\FloatBarrier
\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.2}
\begin{tabularx}{\textwidth}{l X l}
\toprule
\textbf{Component} & \textbf{Model / Part Number} & \textbf{Qty} \\
\midrule
Microcontroller & ESP32 WROOM-32 DevKit v1 (SPI/I2C/ADC/GPIO) & 1 \\
Heart Rate + SpO2 & MAX30102 breakout board (I2C 0x57) & 1 \\
IMU (Fall + Tremor) & MPU6050 breakout board (I2C 0x68) & 1 \\
IR Temperature & MLX90614 breakout board (I2C 0x5A) & 1 \\
VOC + Humidity & BME688 breakout board (I2C 0x76) & 1 \\
UV Sensor & VEML6075 breakout board (I2C 0x10) & 1 \\
Grip Strength & FSR 402 force sensor + 10k resistor (ADC GPIO34) & 1 \\
Galvanic Skin Response & Grove GSR v1.0 or custom 2-electrode (ADC GPIO35) & 1 \\
Bioelectrical Impedance & AD5933 impedance converter (I2C 0x0D) & 1 \\
Near-IR Wound & 850nm LED + BPW34 photodiode + opamp (ADC GPIO36) & 1 \\
OLED Display & SSD1306 0.96 inch 128x64 (I2C 0x3C) & 1 \\
LiPo Battery & 3.7V 1000mAh LiPo + TP4056 charger & 1 \\
Charging Module & TP4056 with protection, USB-C input & 1 \\
3.3V Regulator & AMS1117-3.3 or ESP32 onboard VIN & 1 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

\subsection{Wiring and Pin Configuration}

All I2C sensors share the SDA and SCL bus on GPIO21 and GPIO22 respectively. Each sensor has a unique I2C address allowing coexistence on one bus.

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={ESP32 Pin Assignments}]
// I2C Bus (shared):
GPIO21 (SDA) -> MAX30102, MPU6050, MLX90614, BME688, VEML6075, AD5933, SSD1306 SDA
GPIO22 (SCL) -> MAX30102, MPU6050, MLX90614, BME688, VEML6075, AD5933, SSD1306 SCL
3.3V -> VCC of all I2C modules | GND -> GND of all I2C modules

// Analog Inputs:
GPIO34 (ADC1_CH6) -> FSR 402: one leg to 3.3V, other to GPIO34 (10k pull-down to GND)
GPIO35 (ADC1_CH7) -> GSR sensor signal output
GPIO36 (ADC1_CH0) -> NIR photodiode amplifier output

// NIR Wound Healing Circuit:
GPIO32 (OUTPUT) -> 850nm LED anode via 100 ohm current-limiting resistor
BPW34 photodiode -> cathode to 3.3V, anode to inverting input of LM358
LM358 opamp -> configured as transimpedance amplifier, gain 100k
LM358 output -> GPIO36

// Power:
LiPo 3.7V -> TP4056 BAT+ BAT-
TP4056 OUT+ OUT- -> AMS1117-3.3 IN GND
AMS1117-3.3 OUT -> ESP32 3.3V pin
USB-C -> TP4056 IN+ IN- for charging
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Firmware Architecture}

The Vital32 firmware is written in Arduino C++ using the ESP32 Arduino Core. The main loop runs at 50Hz. Sensor reads are distributed across ticks using a scheduler to avoid I2C bus contention.

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Vital32 Main Loop}]
void loop() {
  uint32_t t = millis();
  // Every tick (20ms):
  readMPU6050();       // accel + gyro at 50Hz for fall detection
  runFallDetector();
  // Every 1 second:
  if (t % 1000 == 0) {
    readMAX30102(); readMLX90614(); readGSR();
    readFSR(); calculateHRV(); runAnomalyScorer(); updateOLED();
  }
  // Every 5 seconds:
  if (t % 5000 == 0) {
    readBME688(); readVEML6075(); readNIR();
    readBIA(); runSeizureDetector(); // LSTM on rolling window
  }
  // Every 30 seconds:
  if (t % 30000 == 0) {
    runBioAgeModel(); writeToFirebase();
  }
}
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Fall Detection Algorithm}

Fall detection uses a two-stage algorithm on the MPU6050 accelerometer data. Stage 1 detects a freefall event by checking if the resultant acceleration magnitude drops below 0.4g. Stage 2 detects the impact by checking if the magnitude exceeds 2.5g within 500ms of the freefall. A zero-movement condition sustained for 3 seconds post-impact confirms the fall.

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Fall Detection Implementation}]
bool detectFall(float ax, float ay, float az) {
  float magnitude = sqrt(ax*ax + ay*ay + az*az);
  if (magnitude < 0.4) {
    freefallTime = millis(); freefallDetected = true;
  }
  if (freefallDetected && magnitude > 2.5) {
    if (millis() - freefallTime < 500) {
      impactDetected = true; impactTime = millis();
    }
  }
  if (impactDetected && magnitude < 1.1) {
    if (millis() - impactTime > 3000) {
      freefallDetected = false; impactDetected = false;
      return true; // confirmed fall
    }
  }
  return false;
}
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{HRV Calculation}

Heart Rate Variability is computed from the RR interval series extracted from the MAX30102 PPG signal. RMSSD is computed over a 2-minute rolling window of RR intervals. LF/HF ratio is computed via Welch PSD on the RR series.

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={RMSSD Calculation}]
float calculateRMSSD(float* rr_intervals, int n) {
  float sum_sq_diff = 0.0;
  for (int i = 0; i < n-1; i++) {
    float diff = rr_intervals[i+1] - rr_intervals[i];
    sum_sq_diff += diff * diff;
  }
  return sqrt(sum_sq_diff / (n - 1));
}
// LF band: 0.04-0.15 Hz | HF band: 0.15-0.40 Hz
// Computed using arduinoFFT library on 256-sample RR window
\end{lstlisting}

