\subsection{ESP32 Peripheral Controller Wiring}

The single ESP32 peripheral controller has been split into two independent boards to isolate timing-critical UWB ranging from servo PWM jitter contention.

\subsubsection*{Drivetrain Controller (ESP32 \#1)}

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Drivetrain ESP32 Pin Assignments}]
// Motor Driver (L298N):
GPIO25 (PWM) -> L298N ENA | GPIO26 (PWM) -> L298N ENB
GPIO27 -> L298N IN1 | GPIO14 -> L298N IN2
GPIO12 -> L298N IN3 | GPIO13 -> L298N IN4

// Ultrasonic Sensors (HC-SR04):
GPIO5  TRIG1 / GPIO18 ECHO1 -> Front
GPIO19 TRIG2 / GPIO21 ECHO2 -> Left
GPIO22 TRIG3 / GPIO23 ECHO3 -> Right
GPIO4  TRIG4 / GPIO15 ECHO4 -> Rear

// UWB Modules (DW1000) x2:
GPIO32 (SPI SCK) -> DW1000 SCK | GPIO33 (MOSI) -> DW1000 MOSI
GPIO34 (MISO) -> DW1000 MISO | GPIO35 (CS1) -> DW1000 #1 CS
GPIO2  (CS2)  -> DW1000 #2 CS

// UART to D-Robotics RDK X5:
GPIO1 (TX) -> RDK X5 UART RX | GPIO3 (RX) -> RDK X5 UART TX
Baud rate: 115200
\end{lstlisting}

\subsubsection*{Manipulator Controller (ESP32 \#2)}

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Manipulator ESP32 Pin Assignments}]
// Robotic Arm Servos (MG996R x5 + MG90S x1):
GPIO13 -> Base rotation (MG996R)
GPIO14 -> Shoulder (MG996R)
GPIO27 -> Elbow (MG996R)
GPIO26 -> Wrist pitch (MG996R)
GPIO25 -> Wrist roll (MG996R)
GPIO33 -> Gripper (MG90S)

// Medication Dispenser Servos (SG90 x4):
GPIO16 -> Servo 1 (Slot A) | GPIO17 -> Servo 2 (Slot B)
GPIO18 -> Servo 3 (Slot C) | GPIO19 -> Servo 4 (Slot D)

// TF-Luna ToF Sensor (UART):
GPIO4 (TX) -> TF-Luna RX | GPIO5 (RX) -> TF-Luna TX

// Water Pump Relay:
GPIO12 -> Relay IN (peristaltic pump)

// UART to D-Robotics RDK X5 (second serial port):
GPIO9 (TX) -> RDK X5 UART1 RX | GPIO10 (RX) -> RDK X5 UART1 TX
Baud rate: 115200
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{ROS2 Package Structure}

HollowRover runs ROS2 Humble Hawksbill on Ubuntu 22.04 Server (64-bit) on the D-Robotics RDK X5, which provides native ROS2 support. The dedicated 10 TOPS NPU/BPU allows SphereAI's AI inference (Whisper STT, DistilBERT sentiment analysis) to run in parallel with ROS2 Nav2/SLAM on separate silicon, eliminating CPU contention that would occur on a general-purpose SoC. The complete ROS2 workspace is structured as follows:

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={ROS2 Workspace Structure}]
hollowrover_ws/
  src/
    hollowrover_bringup/      <- Launch files for full system
    hollowrover_description/  <- URDF robot model
    hollowrover_navigation/   <- Nav2 configuration
    hollowrover_protocols/    <- Biomarker-triggered action nodes
    hollowrover_hardware/     <- ESP32 serial bridge nodes (x2)
    hollowrover_firebase/     <- Firebase state subscriber
    hollowrover_arm/          <- 6-DOF arm control node
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{SLAM Configuration}

HollowRover uses SLAM Toolbox in lifelong mapping mode with the STL-19P TOF LiDAR providing scan data at 5000Hz ranging frequency with $\pm$10mm accuracy across a 12m radius. The TOF-based measurement principle ensures that accuracy does not degrade with distance, unlike triangulation-based LiDARs. The 60000Lux anti-glare rating prevents scan corruption in sunlit indoor environments near windows. The critical Nav2 parameters configure the controller frequency at 20.0\,Hz, max forward speed of 0.3\,m/s, and a safety inflation radius of 0.35\,m around obstacles.

\subsection{UWB Localization}

Two DW1000 UWB anchor modules are mounted at known fixed positions. The UWB tag on the Vital32 wearable broadcasts ranging packets. Trilateration is used when both anchors have valid range measurements.

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={UWB Trilateration Algorithm}]
def trilaterate(ax, ay, rA, bx, by, rB):
    d = sqrt((bx-ax)**2 + (by-ay)**2)
    a = (rA**2 - rB**2 + d**2) / (2 * d)
    h = sqrt(max(rA**2 - a**2, 0))
    x = ax + a*(bx-ax)/d
    y = ay + a*(by-ay)/d
    x1 = x + h*(by-ay)/d
    y1 = y - h*(bx-ax)/d
    return x1, y1  # take solution closer to last known position
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Drivetrain: Rocker Suspension}

HollowRover employs a four-wheel rocker suspension system replacing a flat rigid wheel mount. Each side features a rocker arm with a spring-loaded pivot, and a rear differential bar links the left and right rocker assemblies. The differential bar maintains chassis-level balance across uneven terrain, while the spring-loaded pivots maintain independent wheel-ground contact over bumps, doorway lips, and floor transitions. This passive suspension improves traction and stability compared to the original rigid-mount design without adding active control complexity.


\subsection{HollowRover Robotic Arm}

\subsubsection*{Mechanical Specification}

HollowRover is equipped with a 6-DOF robotic arm mounted on the chassis:
\begin{itemize}[nosep,leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item \textbf{Joint 1 --- Base Rotation:} MG996R metal gear servo
  \item \textbf{Joint 2 --- Shoulder:} MG996R metal gear servo
  \item \textbf{Joint 3 --- Elbow:} MG996R metal gear servo
  \item \textbf{Joint 4 --- Wrist Pitch:} MG996R metal gear servo
  \item \textbf{Joint 5 --- Wrist Roll:} MG996R metal gear servo
  \item \textbf{Joint 6 --- Gripper:} MG90S micro servo
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{Dual-Purpose Design}

The arm serves two distinct functions:

\textbf{(a) Caregiving Assist:} The arm retrieves dropped medication or objects from the floor, and hands items (medication, water, personal items) to the user at an accessible height. This reduces the need for the elderly user to bend down or reach for objects.

\textbf{(b) Security Deterrent --- Passive Barrier:} When EntryGuard's face recognition pipeline (Section~\ref{sec:entryguard}, DeepFace) flags an unregistered individual at a monitored chokepoint (e.g., a hallway leading to valuables or sensitive rooms), the arm swings to a blocking position across the pathway. The arm serves as a passive physical barrier that obstructs the intruder's path.

\subsubsection*{Mechanical Constraint --- LiDAR Occlusion}

The arm rests in a folded/stowed position below the STL-19P LiDAR's scan plane during normal navigation. It only rises to the blocking position when HollowRover is stationary in security-response mode. Navigation and defense states are mutually exclusive: the rover must be stationary before the arm deploys, so no LiDAR occlusion conflict occurs during active navigation.

\subsubsection*{Trigger Sensor and Detection Pipeline}

A TF-Luna single-point ToF sensor (0.2--8m range, UART/I2C interface) is mounted at the designated chokepoint. When the ToF sensor detects a person's presence, the RGB camera feed is routed into the existing DeepFace recognition pipeline. If the detected face is not matched against registered profiles, the security response is triggered.

\subsubsection*{Safety Constraint}

\textbf{The robotic arm is a passive physical barrier only.} It makes no contact with any person, performs no grasping, restraining, or striking action against intruders, and initiates no autonomous defensive decision. The detection event triggers three simultaneous responses:
\begin{enumerate}[nosep,leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item The arm moves to block the pathway (passive barrier only).
  \item An audible alarm is activated.
  \item An instant push notification with live camera feed is sent to the guardian's phone.
\end{enumerate}
All escalation decisions beyond these three actions require explicit human authorization, consistent with the mandatory-human-authorization rule stated in Section~\ref{sec:security}.

% ============================================================
% SECTION 5: SPHEREAI
% ============================================================
\clearpage
\section{SphereAI: Implementation Guide}

SphereAI is the affective computing layer of LifeSphere. It implements a TriAgent architecture with three concurrent processing agents fused by a meta-classifier. The Personality Mirror feature has been removed from this version on ethical and privacy grounds; SphereAI learns preferences to improve interaction quality but does not build a deep personality model that could be replicated or shared.

\subsection{Software Dependencies}

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={SphereAI Python Dependencies}]
pip install openai-whisper    # Speech-to-text (Language Agent)
pip install librosa           # Audio feature extraction (Voice Agent)
pip install transformers torch # NLP sentiment + coherence
pip install scikit-learn      # Meta-classifier
pip install firebase-admin    # Firebase SDK
pip install numpy scipy       # Signal processing
pip install sounddevice       # Microphone capture
pip install pyttsx3           # Text-to-speech output
pip install luma.oled         # SSD1306 OLED display
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{TriAgent Fusion Logic}

The MetaClassifier applies dynamic weights based on the prior emotional state to fuse outputs from the Language, Voice, and Biology agents.

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={SphereAI Meta-Classifier}]
class MetaClassifier:
    WEIGHTS = {
        'calm':      {'language': 0.4, 'voice': 0.3, 'biology': 0.3},
        'stressed':  {'language': 0.2, 'voice': 0.3, 'biology': 0.5},
        'grief':     {'language': 0.3, 'voice': 0.4, 'biology': 0.3},
        'isolated':  {'language': 0.2, 'voice': 0.2, 'biology': 0.6},
        'cognitive': {'language': 0.5, 'voice': 0.3, 'biology': 0.2},
    }

    def fuse(self, lang_out, voice_out, bio_out, prior_state):
        w = self.WEIGHTS.get(prior_state, self.WEIGHTS['calm'])
        scores = {}
        for state in EMOTIONAL_STATES:
            scores[state] = (
                w['language'] * lang_out.get(state, 0) +
                w['voice']   * voice_out.get(state, 0) +
                w['biology'] * bio_out.get(state, 0)
            )
        return max(scores, key=scores.get), scores
\end{lstlisting}

% ============================================================
% SECTION 6: ENTRYGUARD AND HOLLOWCORE
% ============================================================
\clearpage
\label{sec:entryguard}
\section{EntryGuard and HollowCore: Implementation Guide}

\subsection{EntryGuard Hardware per Node}

Each EntryGuard node runs an ESP32 WROOM-32 equipped with a PIR sensor (HC-SR501), ultrasonic sensor (HC-SR04), fire sensor (KY-026), and gas sensor (MQ-2). All sensor events are published to Firebase.

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={EntryGuard Node Firmware}]
void loop() {
  bool motion = digitalRead(PIR_PIN);
  int fire = analogRead(FIRE_PIN);
  int gas = analogRead(GAS_PIN);
  long dist = measureUltrasonic();
  if (motion && systemMode == ACTIVE)
    publishAlert("motion", dist, nodeID);
  if (fire > FIRE_THRESHOLD) {
    publishAlert("fire", fire, nodeID); triggerBuzzer();
  }
  if (gas > GAS_THRESHOLD) {
    publishAlert("gas", gas, nodeID); triggerBuzzer();
  }
  delay(100);
}
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{HollowCore Wiring}

HollowCore uses an ESP32 to control relay modules for appliance operation. It listens to Mosquitto MQTT broker running on the D-Robotics RDK X5 and maps Firebase state variables to relay triggers.

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={HollowCore Pin Assignments}]
GPIO26 -> Relay 1 IN (Living room light)
GPIO27 -> Relay 2 IN (Bedroom light)
GPIO14 -> Relay 3 IN (AC / fan)
GPIO12 -> Relay 4 IN (TV power)
GPIO13 -> Relay 5 IN (Main door lock solenoid)
// MQTT Topic: lifesphere/hollowcore/command
// Payload: {"device": "light_1", "state": true}
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{HollowCore Financial Anomaly Detection \& Biometric Security}

HollowCore extends its monitoring beyond the physical environment to the user's financial and digital security. By integrating with the user's banking and subscription services via secure APIs, HollowCore scans incoming transactions and recurring subscriptions in real-time.

\subsubsection*{Transaction Security Features}
\begin{itemize}[nosep,leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item \textbf{Anomaly Detection:} Utilizes an Isolation Forest model trained on the user's historical spending habits to flag unrecognized, out-of-pattern, or suspicious transactions.
  \item \textbf{Smart Notification:} Instantly alerts the user via the LifeSphere app and HollowRover OLED, providing transaction details and a one-tap option to freeze the card or dispute the charge.
  \item \textbf{Biometric Transaction Authorization:} For the user to authorize any new high-risk transaction or subscription manually, HollowCore mandates multi-factor biometric verification. This requires facial recognition (via EntryGuard/HollowRover camera), fingerprint scan, and proximity confirmation from the Vital32 wearable, ensuring maximum financial security.
\end{itemize}

% ============================================================
% SECTION 7: FIREBASE BACKEND ARCHITECTURE
% ============================================================
\clearpage
\section{Firebase Backend Architecture}

The Firebase Realtime Database serves as the central nervous system of LifeSphere. All five subsystems read from and write to a single JSON tree.

\subsection{Firebase Project Setup}
\begin{enumerate}[nosep,leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item Create a new project named LifeSphere at console.firebase.google.com.
  \item Enable Realtime Database. Choose region asia-southeast1 (Singapore).
  \item Set database rules to authenticated-only access.
  \item Download the service account JSON for Python SDK access.
  \item Get the Web API key for ESP32 REST API access.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{ESP32 Firebase Write (Vital32/EntryGuard)}

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={ESP32 Firebase Write}]
#include <FirebaseESP32.h>
#include <WiFi.h>

#define FIREBASE_HOST "your-project.firebaseio.com"
#define FIREBASE_AUTH "your-database-secret"

FirebaseData fbdo;

void writeToFirebase(SensorData data) {
  Firebase.setFloat(fbdo, "/lifesphere/vital32/heart_rate", data.hr);
  Firebase.setFloat(fbdo, "/lifesphere/vital32/spo2", data.spo2);
  Firebase.setBool (fbdo, "/lifesphere/vital32/fall_detected", data.fall);
}
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Python Firebase Read (SphereAI/HollowRover)}

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Python Firebase Read}]
import firebase_admin
from firebase_admin import credentials, db

cred = credentials.Certificate('serviceAccountKey.json')
firebase_admin.initialize_app(cred, {
    'databaseURL': 'https://your-project.firebaseio.com'
})

ref = db.reference('/lifesphere/vital32')

def on_vital32_change(event):
    data = event.data
    if data.get('fall_detected'):        dispatch_fall_protocol()
    if data.get('anomaly_score', 0) > 0.9: dispatch_emergency_protocol()
    if data.get('seizure_prob', 0) > 0.85: dispatch_seizure_protocol()

ref.listen(on_vital32_change)
\end{lstlisting}

% ============================================================
% SECTION 8: AI MODEL PIPELINE
% ============================================================
\clearpage
\section{AI Model Pipeline: Training and Deployment}

All AI models in LifeSphere are trained offline and deployed as TensorFlow Lite models on the respective hardware. The AI pipeline is the brain of the ecosystem, transforming raw sensor data into actionable medical and emotional insights.

\subsection*{Impact on Humanity}

The AI Pipeline represents a paradigm shift in personal healthcare. By utilizing multi-timescale inference (short, medium, and long-cycle), the pipeline learns the user's unique biological baseline. This means LifeSphere doesn't just compare the user to a generic population---it compares the user to their own healthy state, detecting subtle deviations that precede critical events, thus democratizing predictive healthcare.

\subsection{Isolation Forest Anomaly Detector}

The Isolation Forest model runs on Vital32 (via TFLite) and serves as the primary real-time anomaly detector. It is trained on the user's own biometric data collected during the first 30 days of normal use.

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Isolation Forest Training}]
from sklearn.ensemble import IsolationForest
import numpy as np

def train_isolation_forest(baseline_data):
    model = IsolationForest(
        n_estimators=100, max_samples='auto',
        contamination=0.05, random_state=42
    )
    model.fit(baseline_data)
    return model

def get_anomaly_score(model, sample):
    raw = model.score_samples([sample])[0]
    return 1 - (raw + 0.5)  # normalize to 0-1
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Pre-Seizure LSTM}

The pre-seizure detection LSTM is trained on the CHB-MIT Scalp EEG Dataset and the Epilepsy iEEG Prediction dataset. The model takes 5-minute rolling windows of HRV, accelerometer, and skin temperature features as input.

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Pre-Seizure LSTM Model}]
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import LSTM, Dense, Dropout

def build_seizure_model():
    model = Sequential([
        LSTM(64, input_shape=(300, 5), return_sequences=True),
        Dropout(0.3),
        LSTM(32, return_sequences=False),
        Dropout(0.3),
        Dense(16, activation='relu'),
        Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')  # seizure probability
    ])
    model.compile(optimizer='adam',
                  loss='binary_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy', 'AUC'])
    return model
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{SphereAI Emotional State Classifier}

The Voice Agent utilizes Librosa to extract MFCC, pitch, energy, tempo, and zero-crossing rate. The Language Agent uses a HuggingFace DistilBERT model for sentiment analysis. Cognitive assessment computes unique word ratio, topic repetition, and semantic coherence.

\subsection{Model Performance Summary}

\FloatBarrier
\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.2}
\begin{tabularx}{\textwidth}{l X X X}
\toprule
\textbf{Model} & \textbf{Architecture} & \textbf{Output} & \textbf{Threshold} \\
\midrule
Anomaly Detector & Isolation Forest (100 trees) & Score 0--1 & 0.7 / 0.9 \\
Pre-Seizure LSTM & 2$\times$LSTM (64,32) + Dense & Prob 0--1 & 0.85 \\
Emotional Classifier & Weighted 3-stream fusion & State category & Highest \\
Cortisol Estimator & Gradient Boost (200 trees) & ng/dL est. & 15m update \\
Biological Age Clock & Ensemble (RF + XGBoost) & Age in years & Daily update \\
Cognitive Tracker & Statistical drift (CUSUM) & Deviation score & 2-sigma \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

% ============================================================
% SECTION 9: MATHEMATICAL FOUNDATIONS
% ============================================================
\clearpage
\section{Mathematical Foundations}

\subsection{Biometric Signal Processing}

Heart Rate Variability is computed from the RR interval time series extracted from the MAX30102 PPG waveform. The primary HRV metrics are:

\begin{equation}
\text{RMSSD} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{N-1}\sum_{i=1}^{N-1}(RR_{i+1} - RR_i)^2}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
\text{LF/HF} = \frac{P_{LF}\,[0.04\text{--}0.15\,\text{Hz}]}{P_{HF}\,[0.15\text{--}0.40\,\text{Hz}]}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
C_{\text{est}} = f(\text{RMSSD},\,\text{GSR}_{\text{baseline}},\,T_{\text{skin}},\,\text{sleep\_efficiency})
\end{equation}

\subsection{Isolation Forest Anomaly Score}

\begin{equation}
s(x, n) = 2^{-\frac{E[h(x)]}{c(n)}}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
c(n) = 2H(n-1) - \frac{2(n-1)}{n} \quad \text{where} \quad H(n) = \ln(n) + 0.5772
\end{equation}

Scores $s(x, n) > 0.7$ trigger a soft alert. Scores $> 0.9$ trigger an emergency protocol dispatch.

\subsection{Medication Adherence Entropy}

\begin{equation}
H(X) = -\sum_{i} p(x_i) \log_2(p(x_i))
\end{equation}

High entropy indicates irregular adherence. Low entropy indicates consistent adherence.

\subsection{UWB Trilateration}

\begin{equation}
(x - a_x)^2 + (y - a_y)^2 = r_A^2
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
(x - b_x)^2 + (y - b_y)^2 = r_B^2
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
a = \frac{r_A^2 - r_B^2 + d^2}{2d} \quad \text{where} \quad d = \text{dist}(\text{Anchor}_A,\,\text{Anchor}_B)
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
x = a_x + \frac{a(b_x - a_x)}{d}, \quad y = a_y + \frac{a(b_y - a_y)}{d} \pm h
\end{equation}

% ============================================================
% SECTION 10: PRESCRIPTION OCR
% ============================================================
\clearpage
\section{Prescription OCR and Automated Medication Reminders}

A critical challenge in elderly medication management is the initial setup burden: manually entering every medicine name, dosage, and timing is error-prone and discourages adoption. LifeSphere addresses this through a one-time prescription photograph workflow. The user photographs their prescription once, and the system automatically extracts and creates a complete medication schedule. Manual entry remains available as an alternative, and all extracted data is fully editable to account for handwriting recognition errors.

\subsection*{Feature Overview}
\begin{itemize}[nosep,leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item User photographs prescription once using HollowRover camera or mobile app.
  \item Vision AI model extracts: medicine name, dosage, frequency, duration, instructions.
  \item Medication schedule is automatically created in Firebase and synced to HollowRover.
  \item User reviews and edits extracted data via HollowCore app before confirming.
  \item HollowRover begins autonomous medication delivery on the confirmed schedule.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{System Overview}

The prescription OCR pipeline runs on the D-Robotics RDK X5 and uses a combination of image preprocessing, an OCR engine, and a large language model for structured data extraction. The pipeline is designed to handle the notorious variability of doctor handwriting by using an LLM to interpret context rather than relying on raw OCR output alone.

\subsection{OCR Pipeline and Data Extraction}

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Prescription OCR Pipeline}]
import pytesseract, cv2, base64, requests
from PIL import Image
import firebase_admin
from firebase_admin import db

def preprocess_image(image_path):
    img = cv2.imread(image_path)
    gray = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    denoised = cv2.fastNlMeansDenoising(gray, h=10)
    _, thresh = cv2.threshold(denoised, 0, 255,
                              cv2.THRESH_BINARY + cv2.THRESH_OTSU)
    return thresh

def extract_text_ocr(image_path):
    processed = preprocess_image(image_path)
    raw_text = pytesseract.image_to_string(processed,
                                           config='--psm 6 --oem 3')
    return raw_text

def parse_prescription_with_llm(raw_text):
    prompt = f"""Extract medication details from this prescription text.
    Return ONLY valid JSON in this exact format:
    {{
      "medications": [{{
        "name": "medicine name", "dosage": "500mg",
        "frequency": "twice daily", "times": ["08:00", "20:00"],
        "duration_days": 7, "instructions": "take with food",
        "confidence": 0.92
      }}]
    }}
    Prescription text: {raw_text}"""
    response = call_llm_api(prompt)  # Gemini Flash or GPT-4o mini
    return parse_json_response(response)

def create_medication_schedule(medications, user_id):
    ref = db.reference(f'/lifesphere/medication_schedule/{user_id}')
    for med in medications:
        ref.push({
            'name': med['name'], 'dosage': med['dosage'],
            'times': med['times'],
            'duration_days': med['duration_days'],
            'instructions': med['instructions'],
            'confirmed': False, 'active': False,
        })
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Reminder Schedule Integration}

Once the user confirms the extracted schedule via the HollowCore app, the \texttt{medication\_delivery.py} ROS2 node subscribes to the confirmed schedule and begins autonomous delivery. Each medication slot in the HollowRover dispenser is mapped to a specific schedule entry. The pressure sensor beneath each slot records when medication is removed and updates the adherence log in Firebase.

\subsection{Firebase Medication Schedule Schema}

\FloatBarrier
\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Firebase Medication Schedule Schema}]
/lifesphere/medication_schedule/{user_id}/{med_id}/
  name: "Metformin"
  dosage: "500mg"
  times: ["08:00", "13:00", "20:00"]
  duration_days: 30
  instructions: "take with meal"
  slot: 1                  // HollowRover dispenser slot number
  confirmed: true          // user confirmed OCR extraction
  active: true             // currently in delivery rotation
  adherence_log: {         // updated by pressure sensor
    "2024-07-14": {"08:00": true, "13:00": true, "20:00": false}
  }
\end{lstlisting}

% ============================================================
% SECTION 11: ABSENCE MODE (was Section 12)
% ============================================================
\clearpage
\section{Absence Mode and Autonomous Household Management}

When the primary occupant is away from home for an extended period, LifeSphere transitions into Absence Mode. In this mode, the system continues to maintain the household autonomously by learning from the occupant's historical activity patterns, receiving explicit task instructions from the occupant or designated guardians, and executing household maintenance routines using HollowRover. This transforms LifeSphere from a reactive caregiving system into a proactive household management system during occupant absence.

\subsection*{Absence Mode Capabilities}
\begin{itemize}[nosep,leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item Learns daily household routines from 30 days of historical activity data.
  \item Receives task instructions from occupant via HollowCore app or voice message.
  \item HollowRover executes physical tasks: plant watering, checking appliances, patrols.
  \item EntryGuard enters full active security mode automatically on absence detection.
  \item Daily status report sent to occupant: photos, task completion, security events.
  \item Returns to normal caregiving mode automatically when occupant returns.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Absence Detection}

Absence is detected through a combination of signals: the occupant explicitly activating AbsenceMode via the app, or automatic detection when Vital32 wearable shows no activity for 4+ hours while EntryGuard records a departure event at the front door. The system confirms absence before activating to avoid false triggers from deep sleep or illness.

% ============================================================
% SECTION 12: REMOTE GUARDIAN (was Section 14)
% ============================================================
\clearpage
\section{Remote Guardian and Digital Safety Integration}

LifeSphere extends its safety umbrella beyond the primary elderly user to protect children and other vulnerable family members. Through the LifeSphere mobile app, parents and guardians can remotely configure the ecosystem, add dependent users, and instruct the AI on specific safety parameters to monitor.

\subsection{Remote User Configuration}

A guardian (e.g., a father working abroad) can add a child as a dependent user within the app. The guardian defines specific instructions for SphereAI and HollowCore, such as monitoring for signs of distress, ensuring the child takes medication, or maintaining a secure perimeter via EntryGuard. These instructions are parsed by SphereAI's language agent and converted into active monitoring protocols.

\subsection{AI-Powered Content Safety}

A core component of the Remote Guardian feature is digital safety. Guardians can instruct the AI to restrict and monitor the child's digital devices connected to the HollowCore Wi-Fi network. HollowCore employs network-level filtering and SphereAI analyzes activity patterns to detect and block inappropriate or harmful content in real-time.

\subsubsection*{Digital Safety Features}
\begin{itemize}[nosep,leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item \textbf{Network-Level Filtering:} HollowCore intercepts DNS requests on the home network, blocking access to adult, violent, or malicious websites based on a dynamically updated categorization database.
  \item \textbf{Smart Screen Time:} Guardians can set adaptive screen time limits. HollowCore can gradually throttle bandwidth or disable internet access to specific devices when limits are exceeded.
  \item \textbf{Inappropriate Content Alerts:} If SphereAI detects patterns suggesting exposure to harmful content (e.g., sudden emotional distress correlated with device usage), it alerts the guardian with context and a recommendation to review activity.
\end{itemize}

